formation in other modifiers we have discussed such as the head-complement structure. Not much research was found on the information rates in different languages when reading, but some data suggests [2] that although syllable/sec and character/sec rates may vary wildly, there is much less variation in the time it takes to read a text.%0a%3c %0a%3c In spoken language, a 2019 study analyzing 17 different languages found that they all share a transfer rate of about 39 bits/second [3]. Different languages were not identical, but they noted that the standard deviation of the speaking speeds and information per syllable was much higher than that of the information rate (similar to written language). %0a%3c %0a%3c Although it is difficult to draw exact conclusions, this might suggest that humans as a whole tend to a certain information transfer rate in language. There is a certain natural speed our brain can process information, and so we are much more likely to tend to language that favors that rate. Thus logically constructed languages to be much more efficient such as Ithkuil [4] might be interesting in practice, but it might be unlikely that we can process them properly in the intended manner and speed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [1]http://www.lrec-conf.org/proceedings/lrec2014/pdf/47_Paper.pdf%0a%3c [2]https://irisreading.com/average-reading-speed-in-various-languages/%0a%3c [3]https://advances.sciencemag.org/content/5/9/eaaw2594%0a%3c [4]http://ithkuil.net/%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
